                  <additions>
                    <list>
                      <item xml:id="a01">
                      <desc type="Excerpt">
                      <locus target="#‎155v"/>, column 1, lines 15 and following and <locus target="#156r"/> (lower part)‎ excerpt from <title type="incomplete" ref="LIT4112Salam"/>
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a02">
                      <desc type="Asmat">
                      <locus target="#‎156r"/>, upper: Asmat prayer for safety in travel, based on Ps. 59:1–2‎
                      <foreign xml:lang="gez">
                        ‎የቆጠጢና፡ ስር፡ ሰኞ፡ በ፱፡ ጥላ፡ ምሰህ፡ ማሰደር፡ ማክሰኞ፡ በዘጠኝ፡ ጥላ፡ ንቀል፡ ‎‎ባረብ፡ ሰፍተህ፡ ያዝ፡ ምንገድ፡ ሲህዱ፡...አድኅነኒ፡ እግዚኦ፡ እምጸርየ፡ መሐመድ፡ ‎‎ወአንግፈኒ፡ እምእለ፡ ቆሙ፡ ላዕሌየ፡ አሕመድ፡...‎
                      </foreign>
                      ‎“Take the root of a plant, first dig out the ground on Monday. On ‎Tuesday when the shadow is at 9, cut the root. Sew the root onto ‎Moroccan leather. When you travel, take seven small stones and ‎stand upon a big boulder and recite ‘O Lord, Save me from my ‎enemy, Mohammad; and rescue me from the one who stands before ‎me, Ahmed. Save me from the works of the sinner, Sayid. And save ‎me from blood, Allah Achbar.’ Recite ‘Allah Achbar’ seven times ‎in four directions. Throw one stone in each direction; keep the ‎three stones with your mantle.” ‎
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a03">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#‎157v"/>, col. 1, top seven lines: Prayer Against the Tongue of People <foreign xml:lang="gez">‎‎ልሳነ፡ ሰብእ፡</foreign>, beginning‎ <foreign xml:lang="gez">‎ስመ፡ አብ፡ ወወልድ፡...ጸሎት፡ በእንተ፡ ልሳነ፡ ሰብእ፡ ምቀኛ፡ ወተንኮለኛ፡...‎</foreign>
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a04">
                      <desc type="Asmat">
                      <locus target="#‎157v"/>, bottom of column one–column two: Repeat of Asmat prayer ‎for protection in travel, in the top nine lines of <locus target="#156r"/>, written in a ‎later hand in blue ink‎
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a05">
                      <desc type="Excerpt">
                      <locus target="#‎158r"/> (except for last three lines of the second column): Excerpt ‎from ‎<title type="incomplete" ref="LIT2736RepCh20"/>, mixed with excerpts from <title type="incomplete" ref="LIT1113Anqasa"/>, written by a later hand in ‎blue ink
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a06">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#‎158r"/>, col. 2, bottom three lines through <locus target="#158v"/>, and <locus target="#155v"/>, column ‎‎1, the 15 lines in blue ink: Excerpt from Petition and Supplication, ‎Sǝ’ǝlät wa-‘äsǝtäbqu‘otat, <foreign xml:lang="gez">ስእለት፡ ወአስተብቍዖት፡</foreign>, written by a later ‎hand in blue ink‎
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e01">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#ir #iv #iiv(erso) #157r #159r #160r #160v"/> blank except for scrawls‎
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a07">
                      <desc>
                      <locus target="#iir(ecto)"/> Note of certification: “If someone wants to read or recite ‎this Psalter, it is corrected properly‎"
                      <foreign xml:lang="gez">‎አሁን፡ ግን፡ ይህነን፡ ዳዊት፡ የደገመ፡ ሰው፡ በደ(ም)በኛ፡ ሁኖ፡ ታርሟል፡ ዕዩ፡‎</foreign>
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a08">
                      <desc type="Asmat">
                      <locus target="#‎159v"/>: Asmat prayer for success in argument in court, in a later ‎hand
                      <foreign xml:lang="gez">‎ሰላም፡ ለምድር፡ ዳእደ፡ በድጋጼ፡ ምድር፡ ትረደ፡ ዘካራን፡ ዘካራን፡ ዘካራን፡ አጥባቄን፡ ‎‎(አጥማቂ?)፡ ዮሀንስ፡ ረዳኤ፡ ጊዎርጊስ፡ (sic)...‎</foreign>
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="a09">
                      <desc type="Record">
                      <locus target="#‎156v"/> (17 lines): Will of Wäyzäro Kǝbitu‎
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e02">
                      <desc>
                      ‎Psalm 118 contains the spiritual meanings of the Hebrew letters‎
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e03">
                      <desc>
                      ‎Numbered quires: quires 1–13‎
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e04">
                      <desc>
                      ‎words of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#1v #‎‎33v #34v #36r #36v"/>, etc.);
                      and lines of text are written interlinearly (<locus target="#‎‎10r #39r #49v #50v #60r"/>, etc.);
                      and in the upper margin with a ‎symbol (+) marking the location where the text is to be inserted (<locus target="#‎‎48v"/>, line 16), and in another case where the symbol (┴) is used (<locus target="#‎‎58r"/>, line 19);
                      erasure markings are visible (<locus target="#16v #82r"/>);
                      text has ‎been removed (e.g., <locus target="#14r #38r #134r"/>)‎
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                      <item xml:id="e05">
                      <desc>
                      ‎The scribe regularly has to complete a line of text on another line. ‎Much of the problem is addressed through the selection of an ‎
                      appropriate aspect ratio for the codex combined with an appropriate ‎script size. But, where the line of text is still too long, the
                      scribe ‎completes the line of text above or below the end of the line ‎‎(throughout)‎
                      </desc>
                      </item>
                    </list>
